Items.Title: EF Placement Test
Items.Body:
How to take the test:
1. Go to http://placement.ef.cn (CN) or http://placement.ef.com (RU& ID)
Note: EF Placement Test consists of Grammar and Vocabulary, Listening, and
Reading. The test must be completed in 30 minutes – 10 minutes for each section.

2. Click the ‘Start’ button to go to the next page

3. Students need to fill in their name, age, phone number, and email address
Note: CC will need the student’s phone number OR email address to be able to view
their results. Please ensure the student inputs their correct information.

4. Click ‘Next’ to start the test!

 

5. Once a student has finished each section of the test, they will be able to see their
level instantly

 

6. Click ‘Next’ to continue to the next section
7. Please remind the student to click ‘Submit’ once the test is done

 

8. They will be taken to below page once they have clicked ‘Submit’

 

How to view the test result:
1. Go to http://admin.placement.ef.cn (CN) or http://admin.placement.ef.com (RU& ID)

2. Input student’s email address OR mobile number to view their results
Note: please be reminded to input the email address or mobile number that the
student used on their test. Either email address OR phone number is sufficient.

Items.Title: Logging In & Logging Out
Items.Body:
Log in with your EF ID. The app will remember the name and password for the two most recent users (so you can share an iPad with your brother or sister if they are studying at EF). You will be able to switch users by tapping Log Out on the bottom of the menu. You can add New user to log-in; the most recent two log-ins will always be saved without needing to re-enter your password every time.

If you studied more than one Trailblazers books, you can go back to previous books and assignments. When logging in, the app will give you an option to choose among the books you studied.

To log out, click on the Account icon in the top-right corner to open the menu and log-out at the bottom of the screen.

Items.Title: App Download & Setup
Items.Body:
The EF Progress Test app is not an open app one can find in Apple App Store. Schools must download the app via the EF Apps icon in the home screen and click on EF Progress Test for download. 

Upon downloading the app, please select the correct country, city and school name of your center to complete the setup. If the information is inaccurately inputted, please delete the app and reinstall; otherwise, teachers will not be able to find their scheduled tests in the app.

Items.Title: Start A Progress Test
Items.Body: Upon completing the content download, teachers need to log in with their username and password to start a test. Once logged in, teachers should click on Start Test, select the test group and Invite Students to deploy the progress test.

Items.Title: Preview Mode
Items.Body:
Teachers are encouraged to go through the test questions before the test using the Preview Test function. The questions and layout in preview mode are identical to the actual test. The only differences are:

  1. There is no timer,
  2. Users will not be able to submit the test.

Items.Title: Taking the Test
Items.Body: Students can join the test by selecting I’m a student on their iPads. Students will need to select their group and name as well as try whether the audio works on their devices before entering the actual test page. Due to courtesy, we advise schools and PAs to remind students to bring their own headphones prior to the tests.

Items.Title: Student Test Navigation Bar
Items.Body:
Once students enter the test, things should seem familiar because test types are similar if not exactly identical to what they see in their online homework. 

One element that is different however is that students can jump to different questions rather than doing it in order. Students can view the test via the navigation bar that sits at the bottom of the screen. Once clicked on, students can maneuver their way to different parts of the test by clicking on a different question bubble. 

Tests will be submitted under two circumstances:

  1. the 30-minute test time is up, or
  2. all questions are filled out and ready for submission. Students will not be able to submit if there are questions left unanswered.

Items.Title: The EF Progress Test app Introduction
Items.Body: The EF Progress Test app is an iPad application that streamlines the test experience, classroom management as well as administration. It will replace the current Spotlight app as E1’s primary progress test application. Students will see familiar test types they’ve seen in their online homework, whereas teachers will be able review the test before class and track students’ test completion progress in-app during the test. After the tests are completed, the results will be automatically graded and uploaded to ODIN+, and teachers and PAs will have access to student progress tracking via the progress test viewer and ODIN+.

Items.Title: Monitoring Students’ Test Progress
Items.Body: Once tests begin, teachers can monitor students’ progress on the teacher iPads during the test. It will show student progress through the progress bar as well as test completion notification and status. Once teachers see a student finishes his/her test on the teacher iPads, they can walk over to collect the student’s iPad. Moreover, teachers can also approach students who are stuck, encouraging them to move on and come back to that question later or attending to their needs.

Items.Title: How do I update the EFProgress Test App?
Items.Body:
The update procedure is exactly identical to the download procedure. Depending on the iOS version on your iPads, the system may either ask you to accept the installation or automatically installs itself, or you will have to manually download the app via EF App Store.

Once the app is updated, please make sure the test content is updated as well as shown below.

Items.Title: What do I do if the teacher cannot log in?
Items.Body:
First, please check whether the iPad is successfully connected to school WiFi by trying to access websites (e.g. Bing) in Safari. If the Internet is connected and the issue persists, chances are the school code was incorrectly inputted during the setup process.

Please check the school code on the landing page by tapping on app version on the bottom right corner before choosing I’m a student/I’m a teacher. A pop-up window will display all the detailed settings of the app including the school code. If the school code is indeed incorrect, please delete the app and reinstall. 

If all the information is correctly inputted but the teacher still cannot log in, please change device and file a ticket on E1 Help Center to report this issue.

Items.Title: What do I do if the teacher cannot see the test after a successful login?
Items.Body:
The root cause of this issue is identical to teacher login failure. First, please check whether the iPad is successfully connected to wifi by trying to access websites (e.g. Bing) in Safari. If the Internet is connected and the issue persists, chances are the school code was incorrectly inputted during the setup process. 

Please check the school code on the landing page by tapping on app version on the bottom right corner before choosing I’m a student/I’m a teacher. A pop-up window will display all the detailed settings of the app including the school code. If the school code is indeed incorrect, please delete the app and reinstall.

If all the information is correctly inputted but the teacher still cannot log in, please change device and file a ticket on E1 Help Center to report this issue.

Items.Title: What do I do if a student keeps getting kicked out from the test session?
Items.Body: When this happens, please change device and reinstall the app on said device. If there are no additional iPads available, please print out the paper version of the Progress Test in Athena.

Items.Title: How do I see the Progress Test scores?
Items.Body: Once the tests are submitted, the scores will be automatically uploaded to school service and can be viewed in ODIN+ immediately after the test.

Items.Title: How can I make changes to the scores after the test?
Items.Body: Teachers have permission to overwrite the scores saved in ODIN+ if app issues caused students to perform poorly on the test. Scores can be changed under the Test Results tab in ODIN+.

Items.Title: Which skill areas are being tested in EFProgress Test app?
Items.Body: EFProgress Test app tests students on listening, reading, grammar and vocabulary. The scores on these four skills are automatically uploaded to ODIN if the test was administered via the app. Speaking is being assessed throughout the unit, especially during the two speaking assessments, and the grading rubrics are provided in Athena. Writing is part of the unit progress test, and the topics and grading rubrics are provided in Athena as well. The scores on speaking and writing will have to be manually inputted into ODIN+ once the scores are graded.

Items.Title: If a progress test is taken electronically, will the full test be viewable after submission, or will the teachers only have access to the scores?
Items.Body: Yes, if the test is taken on the iPads, both the teachers and PAs will have access to the Progress Test Teacher Viewer page in ODIN+ which displays all the details of the test for each student.

Items.Title: How do I detect where the issues are?
Items.Body: We provided a simple diagnostic tool inside the app that can help users diagnose the root cause to issues. Please click on the Run a Diagnostic button on the upper left corner on the select student/teacher page. After running the diagnostic test, please take a screenshot and attach the screenshot with your E1 Help Center ticket.

Items.Title: Where do I see app information?
Items.Body: Users can access detailed app information by clicking on the bottom right corner of the select student/teacher page. The pop-up page will display information including version number, school code, etc.

Items.Title: What do I do if the app crashes?
Items.Body: First, please kill the app by double-clicking the home button and swipe the EF Progress Test app upwards until it disappears; and then, restart the app. Please note that the app takes up to one minute for the student avatar to unlock after a crash. If the issue persists after the app restarts, please change device and reinstall the app on said device.

Items.Title: Trailblazers’ App Intro
Items.Body:
EF Trailblazers App is a place where you can do your homework, check your progress, further practice your listening skills, while earning points to unlock exciting rewards.  Bite size downloadable assignments will allow you to do homework anytime and anywhere with no access to the Internet. Variety of engaging activities, immediate feedback, and opportunities to correct mistakes right away will help increase your learning outcomes. The listening tab will give you access to downloadable audio recordings and scripts of text passages of your Trailblazer’s book to help you read and listen along at home. And motivational framework will offer rewarding prizes for all the hard works you’ve done. Doing homework has never been so engaging, effective and convenient!

Downloading the App

Items.Title: Student Progress Tracking Features and Progress Test Viewer
Items.Body: Progress Test Viewer is a tool that we developed to view and analyze how well your Trailblazers groups perform in their Progress Test to help you understand the strengths and weaknesses of both individual students and the group as a whole.

Items.Title: Where to Find It
Items.Body: Progress Test viewer is accessed through your Trailblazers group page in ODIN+. Once you’re there, click Test Results tab and choose the unit you’d like to review. Click on the magnifying glass on top row next to the unit number.

Items.Title: Group View
Items.Body:
The home page on the Progress Test Viewer shows the average score and overall performance of the group.

You can use this page to review a group's test performance, highlighting questions the group answered well, and emphasizing questions the whole group struggled with.

This will help you plan review lessons and activities to focus on common mistakes.

The top row shows the average score of the 4 skills. Click on the component or scroll down to view details on how the group performs on individual tasks and questions – how many students got the answer for that particular question correct.

For questions with more than one mark available, the student must have got full marks to be considered correct in this view.

Click on a question to view more details on what the question is.

 

Click Answers tab to see what the correct answer is.

 

Click View answer by student to see each student’s answer.

Items.Title: Downloading & Unlocking Homework
Items.Body:
Internet connection is required to download assignments and upload scores. Homework assignments will be unlocked after each classroom session at school. This means that students cannot rush ahead and try to complete homework activities for content they have not yet studied in class.

Assignment unlocked. Tap on it to start downloading.

Assignment locked and unavailable for downloading.

Warning band will warn of no Internet connection.

You will always see the most recent scores for each activity.

Items.Title: Individual View
Items.Body:
To see how each student performs individually, click on their name on the left column on the homepage. You can use this page to review individual students’ test performance and also, it gives you information to share feedback on individual students during parent-teacher conferences.

 

As with the group view, the top row shows the average score of the 4 skills of that particular student and how they are compared to the group’s average percentage. Click on the component or scroll down to see details on how the student performs on individual tasks and questions.

Click on a question to view more details on what the question is. Click on Answers tab to see the student’s answer and whether it’s the correct answer.

Items.Title: Progress Reports
Items.Body:
When you have entered a student’s score for each skill in the progress test in ODIN+, their parents will receive a Progress Report notification that asks them to check it on their EF Parents App. With Trailblazers, a progress report is generated and sent every unit.

 

Once parents are logged in to their EF Parents App, click on Progress to see their child’s progress results. They will be taken to the overall score of the current unit of the book their child is studying.

The top row shows the total score of their child’s performance for that unit and overall explanation, followed by the scores the student gets on 6 skill areas. To view full report that contains more details on each skill area’s performance, they can click anywhere on the page. As with EF Parents App, the language used in your child’s Progress Reports will follow the language setting in your phone.

The full report contains details on how the student performs in each skill area and an in-depth explanation of their performance. It also reviews their homework performance for that unit.

Items.Title: Progress Tab & Goals
Items.Body:
Every time you open the app, you will land on the Progress tab.  The progress tab is a place to track homework and motivate you to engage more with the app by tracking and setting goals.

Each unit has three goals, focusing on key activities such as completing assignments, completing assignments with a good score, or correcting all  mistakes. Navigate back to the homework page by tapping “Homework” on the navigation bar at the top or by tapping on the goals themselves.

Scroll up and down to move between units if you want to review and re-try other homework assignments.

Items.Title: Updating Scores
Items.Body:
Scores will be saved on the iPad immediately. The next time you are connected to the internet, the app will send the latest scores to our system. Students will always see the most recent score for each activity, which is also what teachers will see in ODIN+.

If you log-in on a different iPad or computer, the scores will be synchronized whenever you are online.

Items.Title: Feedback, Mistakes & Scores
Items.Body:
Immediate feedback will help you study smarter – learn what you did right, and correct any mistakes!  

After each assignment, the app will tell you how well you have performed. The scores range from Excellent! to Good job, Not bad and Keep trying. Keep practicing, and try to achieve Excellent or Good job for every assignment! If you scored Keep trying, review the language learned in class before trying again. 

You will have 2 chances to choose the correct answer. If after that, mistakes were still made, you will be able correct these immediately after completing the homework and tapping on Correct Mistakes. 

The score you see for the activity on the main page shows how many questions you got correct before correcting your mistakes. You can re-try assignments as many times as you want, and the most recent score will always be shown here.

See how well you performed doing the homework and mistakes you need to correct.

Receive feedback after correcting your mistakes.

Items.Title: App Home Screen
Items.Body:
After students log in with their EF ID and password, students will the see the main page of the app. The number in the middle indicates words available to be tested by the students, which are mostly consisted of the Learning words on the word list. Students can enter the vocabulary quiz by clicking on the Test button.

The magnifying glass icon down at the bottom takes students to a searchable Oxford Dictionary embedded inside the app. Students can search for words they wish to study by clicking on the icon.

The tag icon on the upper right corner takes students to the tagging page where all words currently studying are broken down by book and units. Users can also access the settings page by clicking on the icon on the upper left corner.

Items.Title: Points & Rewards
Items.Body:
Get rewarded for doing homework!

Whenever you are doing homework assignments, correcting your mistakes, or listening to audio clips, you will be earning points. You will also be awarded points for being consistent with your homework (doing homework assignments without skipping), completing homework on time, getting Excellent or Good Job and completing your goals.

Once enough points are earned, rewards will become available to download. Those rewards will include digital wallpaper, cut out Trailblazers figures, birthday cards, calendars and many more.

Go to Points Tab to track your points and see what rewards are available.

 

Award Types

Items.Title: Mentor: Words App
Items.Body: The EF Mentor: Words app is a self-paced vocabulary building mobile application that allows students to expand their vocabulary through short vocabulary quizzes and learning progress tracking. The app is based on the foundation of the Oxford Dictionary where students can manually add words they want to study. In addition, Trailblazers students will enjoy the feature of unit-by-unit automatic target vocabulary word push. We encourage students to use the app for 5 to 10 minutes every day to ensure mastery of all the vocabulary taught in their Trailblazers studies.

Items.Title: Vocabulary Tests
Items.Body:
When users click on Test on the home screen, the system will take users directly to a vocabulary quiz consisting of 20 questions drawn directly from the words available to be tested.

The variety of the questions ranges from easier ones such as choosing definition and using audio to select words to more difficult ones including spelling and unscramble. As a word progress through the stages of mastery, the level of difficulty of the activities raises at the same time.

Items.Title: Listen Tab
Items.Body:
The listening tab allows students to listen to and download audio recordings for longer text passages in the book. Content is organized by unit and will unlock based on classroom sessions. All listening passages for the unit will become available after the first lesson of that unit. 

As with homework assignments, students will need an Internet connection to download, but can then access the audio anytime anywhere afterwards.

Items.Title: Doing Homework on the Website
Items.Body: Don’t have an iPad? Not a problem. Go to study.ef.com or study.ef.cn, log in with your EF ID and do homework online.  The functions are exactly identical to the app version with the exception of the downloading function. Since it is a website, it can only function in the online environment. When accessing homework online, make sure to use the latest version of Chrome, Safari or Internet Explorer as your browser.

Items.Title: Downloading the App
Items.Body: The EF Mentor: Words App is available for both iOS and Android devices. If students want to download to iPads, please search under iPhone Apps only in the App Store.

Items.Title: App Design Thinking – Spaced Repetition
Items.Body:
The app is developed on the premise that in second language acquisition, the mastery of words is proven when learners still know the meaning, spelling and usage of a word after an extended period of time. 

Every time after a test, students will receive a summary of the test. Each word has a progress bar to show where it stands on the road to mastery. A word, from freshly added to considered mastered, needs to get through 10 stages. A word moves up by a stage every time students answer the question on that word in the quiz correctly. Vice versa. A word will be knocked down by a stage every time users answer the question on the word incorrectly during the test. 

The length of the bar indicates the progress. When the bar hits the right end of the screen, that means the word is considered mastered. After the words are mastered, students will stop getting tested on those words except for rare review opportunities. In addition, the green color indicates users answered the question on that word correctly during the quiz whereas red means incorrect. 

As words progress through the stages, two things will happen: 1) the intervals between when students will see the same word again increases, from 1-hour internals between Stage 1 and 2 to 40-hour intervals between Stage 9 and 10, and 2) the level of difficulty in the quiz increases as well, from easier tasks such as choosing definitions and using audio to select words to more difficult ones including spelling and unscramble.

Items.Title: Local Language Translations & Accent Preference
Items.Body:
For words in Trailblazers Book 1 through 5, the system will provide local language translations (Simplified Chinese, Russian & Bahasa Indonesian ) in addition to the English definitions and have questions in the vocabulary test revolving around that. 

The system provides translations based on the language setting on the user’s device. If the phone’s language setting is in Russian, we will provide Russian translation in addition to the English definition. 

Furthermore, users can also choose between British and US pronunciation via the settings icon on the upper left of the home screen.

Items.Title: Manually Adding Words
Items.Body:
In addition to Trailblazers target vocabulary pushed by the system, which happens after the first lesson of each unit, students can search for words they want to study and add them to the word list. 

First, tap on the magnifying glass icon on the home screen to access the dictionary. Then, type in the words in the search bar on the top of the page. Once entered, tap on the + icon to add the word to your word list. 

These words added by the students can be found under Your Words in the tagging page.

Items.Title: Trailblazers CEFR Coverage
Items.Body:
CEFR stands for Common European Framework of Reference. CEFR is the internationally accepted standard, originally started as an initiative of the Council of Europe to provide a basis for the mutual recognition of language qualifications, thus facilitating educational and occupational mobility. It is increasingly used in the reform of national curricula and by international consortia for the comparison of language certificates.

The Common European Framework provides a common basis for the elaboration of language syllabuses, curriculum guidelines, examinations, textbooks... It describes in a comprehensive way what language learners have to do in order to use a language for communication and what knowledge and skills they have to develop so as to be able to act effectively. CEFR is used as the standard to compare curricula, and to describe what learners have to do to use a language for communication -- the heart of what EF wants to teach.

Below is the CEFR concordance chart for Trailblazers:

Items.Title: Book Levels & Study Outcome
Items.Body:
Trailblazers is an English language course developed to meet the needs of young teenage learners, and it is designed for students aged 10 to 14 years old. The course takes students from a basic (A1) to an intermediate (B1.2) level of English. There are 8 books in total, 2 per Common European Framework of Reference (CEFR) level, and there are 5 unites per book. 

Along with the transferable skills, school exam type questions and general confidence which Trailblazers develops in students, they will also learn a great deal of language. At each CEFR level, the students learn language based upon CEFR descriptors of skills and grammar. In terms of vocabulary, the 8 books cover around 2500 words in total. And according to the CEFR concordance chart below, Trailblazers covers levels ranging from A1 all the way to B1.2.

Items.Title: Book 2 Overview
Items.Body:
Book 2 is the second book in the CEFR A1 level. This book takes students from catching up with family members to discussing famous people and favourite video games, spending time at home and having fun in a new city. Over 300 words from these topics and key national exams are covered.

Students will learn grammar points such as the present continuous tense, adverbs of frequency, comparatives and imperatives. They will also develop skills related to presenting information and ideas clearly and concisely, resolving conflicts and considering different points of view to make objective judgments.

Items.Title: Book 1 Overview
Items.Body:
Book 1 is the first book in the CEFR A1 level. This book takes students from introducing themselves and talking about pets and school subjects, to spending time with friends and attending parties. Over 300 words from these topics and key national exams are covered.

Students will learn grammar points such as the present simple tense, wh-questions and adverbs of sequence. They will also develop skills related to making formal presentations and using and interpreting non-verbal communication, as well as choosing the most viable option available.

Items.Title: Book 3 Overview
Items.Body:
Book 3 is the first book in the CEFR A2 level. This book takes students from sharing recent holiday stories and discussing music genres, to exploring social media, future careers and school projects. Over 300 words from these topics and key national exams are covered.

Students will learn grammar points such as gerunds and infinitives, past simple verbs, question words and prepositions. They will also develop skills related to decision-making, making presentations, and organizing information.

Items.Title: Trailblazers Overview
Items.Body:
Trailblazers is a comprehensive English language course designed by EF specifically for middle school learners. The course builds its syllabus on engaging real-world topics and exceeds national English curriculum requirements, empowering students to excel in school and beyond.

Classroom sessions focus on communicative learning in an immersive environment. Beyond the classroom, students have access to personalized learning tools, including online vocabulary building and homework applications.

Items.Title: Book 7 Overview
Items.Body:
Book 7 is the first book in the CEFR B1.2 level. This book takes students from weighing the pros and cons of different holiday activities and persuading friends to try new things, to telling funny stories, discussing global issues and giving advice to team members. Over 300 words from these topics and key national exams are covered.

Students will learn grammar points such as conjunctive adverbials, compound conditionals and indefinite pronouns. They will also develop skills related to planning events, drawing specific conclusions from a set of general observations and motivating others to act.

Items.Title: Book 8 Overview
Items.Body:
Book 8 is the second book in the CEFR B1.2 level. This book takes students from asking for favours or help and setting up small businesses, to learning about personality, taking responsibility for mishaps and volunteering in different parts of the world. Over 300 words from these topics and key national exams are covered.

Students will study grammar points such as the future perfect tenses, present hypothetical and first, second and third conditionals. They will also develop skills related to establishing priorities, analyzing data, and evaluating alternatives to suggest solutions to problems.

Items.Title: Book 6 Overview
Items.Body:
Book 6 is the second book in the CEFR B1.1 level. This book takes students from talking about participating in school events and applying to a new school to discussing clothes and fashion, and describing symptoms when going to a doctor. Over 300 words from these topics and key national exams are covered.

Students will learn grammar points such as the future continuous tense, the second conditional with ‘would’ and ‘could’ and present perfect and present perfect continuous tenses. They will also develop skills related to adapting to new situations and settings, drawing conclusions from a set of facts and presenting for a specific audience.

Items.Title: Book 4 Overview
Items.Body:
Book 4 is the second book in the CEFR A2 level. This book takes students from discussing movies and making free time plans to writing and editing short stories, making schedules, attending events, and making friends on holiday. Over 300 words from these topics and key national exams are covered.

Students will study grammar points such as modals of possibility, prepositions of time and the past continuous tense. They will also develop skills related to reviewing ideas and making objective judgments, organizing information and interpreting non-verbal communication.

Items.Title: Book 5 Overview
Items.Body:
Book 5 is the first book in the CEFR B1.1 level. This book takes students from planning day trips and various events, to discovering book genres and museum exhibits, and learning classroom skills. Over 300 words from these topics and key national exams are covered.

Students will learn grammar points such as the past simple and continuous tenses, phrasal modals and superlatives. They will also develop skills related to finding new solutions to problems, recognizing personal strengths and weaknesses, and evaluating and choosing the best available option.

Items.Title: Teachers' Notes
Items.Body: The Trailblazers program provides lesson-by-lesson Teachers’ Notes with suggested timings for all in-class activities. Teachers’ Notes can be found via Athena 2.0 -> Trailblazers 3.0 -> Select a book -> Select a unit -> Select a lesson -> Teachers’ Notes.

Items.Title: Why the new homework is not unlocked after class?
Items.Body:
The mechanism for homework unlocking in the Student App is set for 30 minutes after class since we want to prevent students from doing homework before materials are covered in class. Students can refresh the homework page by simply pulling down on the screen within the app, and new content should be available for download. Please make sure students have Internet access while refreshing. If the unlocking issue persists after following the steps above, please tap on the Account button on the top right corner and select the Diagnostic button to run a quick system diagnostic test (as shown below).

Please take a screenshot of the test result and send it to your Progress Advisor via text or email. Thank you.

Items.Title: Why am I stuck on the bear climbing page (shown below) and couldn’t proceed to the homework page?
Items.Body:
The reason that most likely caused this issue is unopened course.

Since the logic for homework unlocking is 30 minutes after each class period, if students attempt to log in prior to the end of the first class period, they will not be able to progress beyond the bear climbing page. Please refresh 30 minutes after your first class period, and you will be able to get through.

If this issue persists after students’ first class, it might be an issue on the back end of the system. Please contact your Progress Advisor about this as soon as possible.

Items.Title: I don’t have an iPad, is the homework content available online?
Items.Body: Yes, there is a browser version for the student homework. You can access the site at study.ef.com for Russia and Indonesia and study.ef.cn for China. The functions are exactly identical to the app version with the exception that users will have to complete homework in an online environment. When accessed homework online, please use Chrome, Safari or regular IE (not EDGE) as your default browser.

Items.Title: How do I download the EF Trailblazers Student App?
Items.Body:
Please access Apple App Store and search for EF Trailblazers or scan the QR codes below that will directly take you to the download page.

Once downloaded, please click on the app icon to access it. In addition, please activate the auto-update function to ensure you have the latest version of the app. You can activate the function via Settings > iTunes & App Store > activate Updates as displayed the screenshot below.

Items.Title: Why can’t I log in?
Items.Body: Firstly, please check your Internet access by checking whether you can access websites such as bing.com. Secondly, make sure you are not connected to VPN. Thirdly, please check you’ve selected the country you’re enrolled in and typed in your iLab ID and password correctly. If you’ve gone through these three steps above and still cannot log in, please reach out to your Progress Advisor.

Items.Title: What are the technical requirements for  EF Trailblazers Student App/Online School?
Items.Body:
TB3.0 computer system requirements for students (iLab: study.ef.com)

 

Operation system

Windows 7, Windows 8, Windows 10, iOS 8.3+

Browser

IE11, Google Chrome 51+ (Recommended), Safari

Items.Title: Why there is no audio during the listening section of the homework?
Items.Body: Audio issues are generally device/hardware related. Please check whether the Mute button on your device is deselected while the audio is playing (as shown below).

Items.Title: How long does it take for me to master a word?
Items.Body: Technically, students will have to answer a word correctly 10 times before a word is considered mastered in the system. However, if students answer a word wrong once, he/she will have to answer the word correctly once to offset the wrong answer. Therefore, the short answer is minimally 10 times.

Items.Title: Why does my screen show grey and none of my words are showing up?
Items.Body: Please leave the app open and let it sync with the servers for a few minutes. If the issue persists, please contact your Progress Advisor. Thank you.

Items.Title: How do I change my pronunciation setting to either British or American English?
Items.Body: Please tap on the settings icon on the top left corner on the front page to change app settings. Once entered, tap on English to switch between British and American English.

Items.Title: How do I review only the words in a specific book and/or unit?
Items.Body: Please tap on the tagging icon on the top right corner on the front page to view the book and unit you are currently studying as well as all the books and units you’ve been enrolled in previously. You can tap on the specific book and unit that you wish to practice and start practicing words from that book and/or unit.

Items.Title: How do I add my own words?
Items.Body: Please tap on the magnifying glass icon on the front page to access the embedded Oxford Dictionary; and then, type in a word you are looking for in the search bar on the top. Once you found the word you are looking for, tap on the word to access the explanation. Once entered, tap on the + icon to add word, and the word you added will show up under Your Words in the tagging icon.

Items.Title: How come I don’t get any words pushed?
Items.Body: Please confirm your EF ID and password are correctly inputted, and you have access to the Internet. If this issue persists, please report to your Progress Advisor. Thank you.

Items.Title: How do I make the local language translation appear in Mentor?
Items.Body:
The app automatically detects the language setting on your device; in short, if your mobile device is set to your local language, Mentor will automatically provide vocabulary translation of that language. If the local language is currently not set as default on your device, e.g. English, and you wish to change it, please kill the app and change the language setting on your device to your local language. The translation will appear after re-launch. 

Furthermore, since Mentor only provides translations for students at CEFR level A1 and A2, students will NOT receive translations on words for Trailblazers Book 5 or beyond.

Items.Title: I don’t have a portable device, is the content available online via browsers?
Items.Body: Unfortunately, the content is currently available in a smartphone/tablet device application format only.

Items.Title: Will students see rude words?
Items.Body: A profanity filter is integrated into the system that blocks all the rude words in the searchable Oxford Dictionary.
